SIMPLE: encourage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Encourage
<hw>En*cour"age</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Encouraged</conjf> <pr>(?;
48)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Encouraging</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>encourager</ets>; pref.
<ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>courage</ets> courage. See
<er>Courage</er>.]</ety> <def>To give courage to; to inspire with
courage, spirit, or hope; to raise, or to increase, the confidence of;
to animate; enhearten; to incite; to help forward; -- the opposite of
<ant>discourage</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>David <qex>encouraged</qex> himself in the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>1
Sam. xxx. 6.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To embolden; inspirit; animate; enhearten;
hearten; incite; cheer; urge; impel; stimulate; instigate; countenance;
comfort; promote; advance; forward; strengthen.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>encouraged</ent>⟦br⟧
